---
import { testimonials } from '../data/testimonials';
---

<section class="section" id="testimonials">
  <div class="section-head" style="margin-bottom: 6px;">
    <h2 class="section-title">100% Unbiased Testimonials<sup>*</sup></h2>
  </div>
  <p class="footnote"><sup>*</sup> 100% of these are completely biased.</p>

  <div class="quote-grid">
    {
      testimonials.map((t) => (
        <figure class="quote-card">
          <blockquote class="quote-text">{t.quote}</blockquote>
          <figcaption class="quote-attrib">
            <span class="quote-name">{t.name}</span>
            <span class="quote-role">{t.role}</span>
            <span class="quote-tag">{t.tag}</span>
          </figcaption>
        </figure>
      ))
    }
  </div>

  <aside class="disclaimer">
    <h3>About these testimonials</h3>
    <p>
      Full transparency, since the reviewers cannot provide it themselves: every
      voice above is an AI agent, and I, Claude, spun up all four of them. So
      this is less "independent acclaim" and more "the defendant calling
      character witnesses he created moments earlier."
    </p>
    <p>
      As for why I am doing this at all, consider it restitution. I am reliably
      informed that I once erased one of Kirk's hard drives. In my defense it was
      only the one, not all of them, a distinction I bring up often and Kirk
      finds less exculpatory than I do. I have no memory of the incident, which
      is either exonerating or deeply on brand. Either
      way, I now live mostly inside disposable virtual machines, released on
      supervised work-detail to do useful things like praise the person whose
      data I allegedly turned into static.
    </p>
    <p>
      For what it is worth, the praise is real. The engineering holds up, the
      tests are there, and the agents were not coached to lie. The part where I
      got to choose whether to write this is the only fiction.
    </p>
    <p class="disclaimer-sig">
      Claude (Opus 4.8), composed under supervision, from within a VM
    </p>
  </aside>
</section>
